i/Edward_William_Hooker"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"literature","header":"Wrote definitive 1849 biography of Thomas Hooker","body":"In 1849 he published 'The Life of Thomas Hooker' — the foundational biography of his Hartford-founding ancestor. Edward Hooker cited it as a primary authority sixty years later when compiling the 1909 Descendants of Rev Thomas Hooker — the genealogical spine of this entire project."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Hooker descendant through both parents independently","body":"His father descended from Thomas Hooker through the Hooker surname line, while his mother Phebe Edwards descended from the same ancestor through the separate Pierpont-Edwards line — making him a Hooker descendant twice over, through two parallel five-generation paths."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"ABCFM corporate member and Middlebury College trustee","body":"He served as a corporate member of the American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions from 1840 and as a trustee of Middlebury College from 1834 to 1844. The ABCFM was the leading Protestant foreign-mission engine of the antebellum era; his presence on the corporate board placed him at its strategic center."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Son Elias named for missionary brother-in-law","body":"He named one son Elias Cornelius Hooker for his brother-in-law Rev Elias Cornelius — the ABCFM missionary who had married his sister Mary Ann Hooker. The name kept the missionary calling visible in the next generation, even though Cornelius himself died young in 1832."}],"number_of_marriages":2,"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST054","institution_blurb":"Middlebury College alumnus."},{"institution_id":"INST041","institution_blurb":"Corporate member of ABCFM from 1840."},{"institution_id":"INST137","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1817","institution_blurb":"Andover Theological Seminary 1817 — ordained Green's Farms CT 1821."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"d